==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*þunraz'', from Indo-European ''*(s)tenh₂-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[thuner]], Old Saxon [[þunar]] (Dutch [[donder]]), Old High German [[donar]] (German [[Donner]]), Old Norse [[þórr]] (Swedish [[tor]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Sanskrit [[स्तन्]], Greek [[στένει]], Latin [[tonare|tonāre]], Old Church Slavonic [[стенати]] (Russian [[стенать]]), Lithuanian [[steneti]].

===Pronunciation===
*[[IPA]]: /ˈθʊnoɹ/

===Noun===
'''þunor''' ''m''
# [[thunder]]
# a Germanic god, [[Thor]], associated with the Roman [[Jupiter]]

